 was doing his part to gain freedom for the slaves. Being politically outspoken, Guiney was often criticized for his views by other Irish-Americans. His letters reveal not only the experiences and thoughts of an Irish Catholic soldier, but also the hidden tensions within his immigrant community. His views and observations not only illuminate his personal independence of thought, but also the political landscape which he tried to improve.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / Civil War Period (1850-1877).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311074329640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823295326423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823295326/original  a978-3-11-074329-6  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK